The reaction equation for dry methane reforming (DMR) is given in Eq. 7 [10, 11]. In DMR conditions, water generation is often present, so WGS reactions need to be avoided. The role of calcium-looping in DMR can therefore be explored as a potential CO2 feedstock for the reaction. As a result, it can be recovered from various gases after the water has been removed, as well as from various gases emitted by fossil fuelled power plants and large energy intensive industries [11].7CH4g+CO2(g)↔2CO(g)+2H2(g)ΔH298Ko=247kJ·mol-1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
